**Background**.   This exercise in mid-to-low-level design asks you to work with several alternatives to an RTTI-based approach managing choices.  For this assignment, I&#39;ll focus on choosing an MS-Windows-based application for manipulating a file, based on file type and type of operation: e.g., using Excel for opening .xls files, Word for opening .doc files, and Notepad for opening .txt files.  While I&#39;d prefer to focus on the ISC and its needs in this assignment, we don&#39;t yet have a clear sense of what types of files this system might be asked to manipulate, let alone what utilities it will use to transcribe and analyze those files.  And Windows is a convenient platform to work with in this environment, given the extent to which ETSU&#39;s IT departments have standardized on Microsoft software.

**More background:**

The Chain of Responsibility design pattern structures concrete subclasses of an abstract base class as a linked list,

- .each of whose nonfinal elements either
  - .responds to an input that that element is designed to handle, then returns, or
  - .forwards the input (i.e., &quot;passes the buck) to the next element in the chain
- .whose final &quot;Harry S Truman&quot; (i.e,. &quot;The buck stops here&quot;) handles any input that the chain&#39;s non-final elements failed to handle

Problems 1-3 ask you to use the Chain of Responsibility pattern to use a de facto standard Microsoft utility to open a file based on its extension.  To determine what commands Windows operating systems use to open files, I used a registry editing utility to search the Windows registry&#39;s **HKEY\_CLASSES\_ROOT** hive for registry keys named **command.** that are subkeys of a registry key named **shell**. Locations of some or all of these utilities are system-dependent: e.g., all of the commands for opening MS Office files in the above assume the use of MS Office 16.  Similarly, which browsers are installed on a given platform will vary based on the platform&#39;s configuration.

Since I&#39;m allowing you to once again work these problems in your language of choice, I&#39;m leaving it to you to use whatever language-specific library is at your disposal to identify a system call for invoking these commands.  In Python 3, for example, the library routine would be **os.system()**.

Problems:

1. (4 points) Implement a Chain of Responsibility-based program that does the following:

- .Accepts the name of a file.
- .Does one of the following actions:
  - .Identifies the file&#39;s type as known, based on its extension, then
    - .uses the associated utility to open the file,
    - .displays an error message if the open fails
  - .Displays an error message, noting that the file type isn&#39;t recognized.

Other stipulations:

- .If you wish, you may choose other file extensions as a basis for completing this exercise: e.g., **.mht, .mpp., mda, .reg, .zip**.  Windows certainly provides you with enough extensions from which to choose.  Just make sure that  you choose an extension for which a &quot;real&quot; application can be identified.
- .If you choose a file type that could be opened by two or more different applications, settle on one of those applications for that type and run with it.
- .Your application must handle at least four types of files.
- .Each of your chosen file types must be handled by exactly one handler - no more.
- .Each handler must handle exactly one type of file - no more.
- .In your non-final handler class(es), include a setter function that initializes the follow-on file type handler for each handler in the chain.  Use this setter to initialize (i.e. construct) the chain.

1. (2 points)  Same as #1, except rework your logic, eliminating the &quot;next handler&quot; setter in favor of a constructor argument that specifies the next element in the chain.  Do all setup (i.e., initial construction) for the chain as a whole in the instances&#39; constructors.
2. (4 points)  Same as #1, except rework your logic, adding a &quot;side chain&quot; to your implementation:  i.e.,

- .Identify a file type that has a minimum of three possible handlers:  e.g., **.csv, .mp3, .txt.**
  - .Ideally, this should be one of the file types that was supported in problem 1.
  - .Otherwise, do one of two things:
    - .replace one of your handlers in your code for #1 with a handler for this additional file type
    - .incorporate an additional handler into your starting chain
- .This new handler should itself serve as the head of a &quot;side chain of responsibility&quot; that implements a fault-tolerant approach to opening the file:  i.e.,
  - .For each of the possible applications that could handle this type of file, create a non-final handler that does the following:
    - .attempts to invoke the associated application on the file type
    - .on failure, rather than invoking an error message and giving up, passes the file to open to the next handler in the side chain
  - .Terminate the chain with a non-final handler that reports the error.

1. (2 points)   Rework #1, replacing the Chain of Responsibility with a single lookup on a dispatch table.  This dispatch table should map file types to objects that handle those file types.
2. (1 points)   Rework #1, using a switch statement or a nested if statement (your choice) to associate each of the file types with an action.
3. (2 points)   For each of the three approaches to managing choice that were presented in these problems--i.e., Chain of Responsibility; dispatch table;  switch/case (or nested if), describe what you see as that approach&#39;s strengths and limitations.  Be sure to address the following three characteristics of the each approach:  clarity, concision, flexibility.   Note: for credit, you must have completed at least one &quot;reasonable&quot; implementation of 4, 5, and any of 1-3.
